<section xml:id="sec-1-3parametric-questions">
  <title>10.3 Calculus and Parametric Equations</title>

  <exercises xml:id="calculus_parametric">

  <introduction>
    <p>
        We are still interested in lines tangent to points on a curve. They describe how the 
        <m>y</m>-values are changing with respect to the <m>x</m>-values, 
        they are useful in making approximations, and they indicate instantaneous direction of travel.
    </p>
  </introduction>


  <exercise xml:id="sec10-3-concept-mc-01" label="sec10-3-concept-mc-01">
    <title>Exercise: Same curve, different parameterizations.</title>
     <statement>
    <p>
      Two particles move according to the parametric equations
      <m>x=t,\ y=t^2</m> and <m>x=2t,\ y=4t^2</m>.
      Which statement is true?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">
    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p>Both particles trace the same parabola, but they may move along it at different rates.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Correct. Both parameterizations describe the curve <m>y=x^2</m>, but the parameter changes how the curve is traced.</p></feedback>
    </choice>
    <choice correct="no">
      <statement><p>The particles trace different curves because the equations are not identical.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Different parameterizations can describe the same geometric curve.</p></feedback>
    </choice>
    <choice correct="no">
      <statement><p>The second particle traces a line, not a parabola.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Eliminating the parameter still gives <m>y=x^2</m>.</p></feedback>
    </choice>
    <choice correct="no">
      <statement><p>The two particles must move in opposite directions.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>There is no reason they must move in opposite directions.</p></feedback>
    </choice>
  </choices>
</exercise>

